I"E<p>The social brain hypothesis argues that the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/triune-brain-model-classifies-brain-regions-through-evolutionary-lens">evolution of the neocortex</a> is a result of the need to keep track of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/self-play-is-peer-pressure-in-reinforcement-learning">complex social structures of related individuals</a>. In this view, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/pretrained-models-are-universal-computation-engines">reasoning primitives for sociality might have been exapted for general use</a>.</p>
